New CPAs round up in testimonial dinner

The recent passers in the September-October 2023 Licensure Examination for Certified Public Accountants (LECPA) from the University of San Jose-Recoletos’ (USJ-R) Certified Public Accountants (CPA) Review Center gathered for a testimonial dinner held at the Casino Español de Cebu on Wednesday, November 8.

The evening was filled with engaging activities, including the CPA Bingo, a creative spin on the classic game. Instead of numbers, they had to achieve various tasks all centered and related to their CPA journey.

One of the newly admitted CPAs and Josenian alumna, Maria Stella Cabague, emphasized the benefit of having a good support system throughout her academic journey.

“Very important gyod ang support system para nako. Despite sa kalisod sa program, sa kadaghang struggles nga na-experience namo, it was all bearable because we were all together,” she said.

Cabague also highlighted the value of relaxation amid academic challenges.

“Every year, we always go somewhere, manglaag mi, mag-recharge mi, para the next year, mas stronger nami. Despite sa kalisod, naa gihapon mi’y something to look forward [to],” she added.

Another Josenian CPA, Lemwhel Saldon, expressed that integrity is the ethical value he will continue to cherish as a CPA.

“There are many instances that our integrity will be compromised. Admittedly, daghan kaayo’g factors na ma-compromise atong integrity, may it be [because of] self-interest, maybe because of our boss, or maybe because of those who are ahead of us. I just hope that when the right time comes, we caution ourselves and muster the courage,” he said.

Meanwhile, CPA Review Center Director Kristine June Uy imparted her message to all the new CPAs.

“To the new Certified Public Accountants, as one journey ends, another one begins. May it be filled [with] much happiness, friendships, and success,” she said, welcoming them in the profession.

Prior to the testimonial dinner, a “Tribute to New CPAs” took place at the Center for Performing Arts (CfPA), where the CPA passers were recognized for their achievements.

The oath-taking ceremony for the new CPA passers will be held on December 11 at Cebu Parklane International Hotel.

via Rey Martin Rio | FORWARD Staff Writer

USJ-R SSC President wins Cebu Fed elections

The University of San Jose-Recoletos Supreme Student Council (USJ-R SSC) 42nd Congress President, Ninolito Enricko Sanchez was elected as the new Cebu City Federation of Tertiary Supreme Student Government and Councils (CCFTSSGC) President during the SSG Summit 2023 at Golden Prince Hotel Cebu City on Sunday afternoon, November 5.

The event brought together council leaders from various educational institutions to address pressing issues concerning Sugbuanon students and plan future initiatives, including blood donation campaigns and HIV awareness in collaboration with the Cebu City Youth Development Commission (CCYDC).

Sanchez, the President-elect of CCFTSSGC, presented his platform for the establishment of a Student’s Rights and Welfare (STRAW) Hotline to address students’ grievances.

He also expressed his commitment to promoting “social inclusion” and creating safe spaces for minority voices.

“Ang students na gipang-deny og enrollment kay taas ilang hair kay dili fit sa standards sa school and katong mga tawong gipang-discriminate. I wanna fight for these people,” he expressed.

The oath-taking of the newly-elected officers of CCFTSSGC will be held at Fuente Park on December 4.

via Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: USJ-R SSC

Jaguars falter against Webmasters, 59-73

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars fell short against the University of Cebu (UC) Webmasters, 59-73, in the Cesafi 23 Men's Basketball game on Tuesday evening, November 7, at the Cebu Coliseum.

The USJ-R Jaguars absorbed their second loss in seven games as they now sit at the third spot this season, behind the defending champions, the University of the Visayas (UV) Green Lancers (6-0), while the Webmasters are still undefeated (8-0).

Anchoring on the offense of their team captain Justine Langres, along with Klein Gordillo, and Elmer Echavez, had an excellent start as they capped off the opening period with a five-point lead (20-15) and stretched it to leave the Webmasters with eight points (34-26) by halftime.

However, the Jaguars turned cold at the start of the second half as some had foul troubles, which made a loophole in the team’s performance.

Their collapsed offense and defense in the third quarter also created a turning point in the match, allowing the Webmasters to eventually reduce the gap.

“Weakness sa team karon [kay] daghan kaayo'g turnovers, 'nya ang pinakadako sad nga problema is wala'y leadership ang point guards instead nga sila ang mag-coach sa sulod [sa court] nya mataranta na. Dako kaayo'g impact ba and at least kana ma-practice na,” Banua said.

The Webmasters took advantage of this dilemma and erased the Jaguars' advantage to one point, 42-41, before completely taking over the third period.

The opposing squad then went on to build a 13-point lead, 57-44, heading into the final period.

Meanwhile, one of the Jaguars' reliable guards, Karl Ventura, suffered an injury when he dislocated his right index finger during the third period as he attempted to poke the ball from the hands of UC's Ricofer Sordilla.

Despite the Jaguars’ effort in the fourth period through Echavez, Langres, and Karl Cabulao, managing to cut the lead at 56-65, the Webmasters quickly responded with an 8-1 run to seal their victory.

Echavez scored a total of 13 points, while Gordillo added 10 in their losing efforts.

Jaguars' Coach Melo Banua also shared that they will still “fight” and “prepare” for the next game and if the team wants to win, they should step up.

“Dili gihapon mi mo-give up, dako gihapon og chance ang team nga makasulod sa top 4. Also, [with] the team chemistry sa point guard and skills sa mga bata, kay daghan [pa] kaayo ta'g malabay na bola,” he said.

The Jaguars will have a chance at redemption as they take on the Benedicto College (BC) Cheetahs on November 12 at the same venue.

via Khabzeel Clark Payao | FORWARD Probationary Writer

#OnTheGo

Lady Jaguars earn first win in Cesafi 23 Women’s Vball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Lady Jaguars swept the Cebu Institute of Technology-University (CIT-U) Wildcats, 3-0, in their first Cesafi 23 Women’s Volleyball match at the University of Southern Philippines Foundation (USPF) Gymnasium on Sunday, November 5.

The Lady Jaguars won their three-set campaign against the Wildcats by scoring 25-18, 18-25, 25-21.

Cesafi 22 Women’s Volleyball’s Most Valuable Player (MVP) Lounette Marie Abangan grabbed the first point for the Lady Jaguars with her overwhelming spike to the opposing team and continued their momentum to end the first set at 25-18.

The air moved in another direction in the middle of the second set for the Jaguars with their faulty attacks. However, the team capitalized on Alyssa Emboy’s spikes, pouncing on the Wildcats and furthered their win, 25-18.

The Wildcats began the third set with a booming point and rallied to equalize the game with the Jaguars, both exhibiting quick receives and strong net defense, but the Jaguars triumphantly clinched the third set with a score of 25-21.

Meanwhile, Abangan shared that her team needed to exert more effort in the game for their opponent was not a team to be complacent about.

“Nagka-bagat mi last year, di jud sila sayon nga kontra, sa among expectation. Laban ra gihapon mi, ug dili namo i-underestimate ang among kontra,” Abangan said.

Abangan added that they were anxious as it was their first game of the season, along with the addition of their new players.

“First ever game man gud ni namo sa season, so dili gihapon mawala ang kulba kay daghan pud og napuno sa team. Do what we can lang sa pagka-karon, labi na kay first game pa,” she said.

She further wished the team to be focused on defending their Cesafi championship title.

Moreover, Jaguars’ Head Coach Roldan Potot has one reminder for the team in this year’s women’s volleyball games.

“I always remind the girls nga dili makumpyansa kay lisod ang ikatulo. Nag-back-to-back mi last year. Hopefully, mao na amo gi-target ron nga makuha ang ikatulo. One game at a time,” Potot said.

The Lady Jaguars will battle against the University of Cebu (UC) Webmasters on November 12 at the same venue.

[JOSENIANS MOVING FORWARD]

Crossword of Choices: The Growth of an Indomitable Spirit
by Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Time-walking on a seemingly “deja vu” adventure as if he is a game character who respawned in the exact same arena was not an easy adjustment for 24-year-old gamer Tristan Seth Fernandez.

His new encounters inside the campus are a testament now as he embarks on the same journey as it was seven years ago.

From the pursuit of his career in the eSports industry to achieving his dream to become a professor, Tristan’s story is a paragon of resiliency that teaches Josenians how to turn setbacks into opportunities and how to turn those stumbling blocks into stepping stones toward their goals.

The Baffling Dilemma

Reminiscing a certain time frame when he is tested on whether to continue his studies or pursue a career in the eSports industry marked the start of this life-changing dilemma.

At the age of 18, Tristan encountered this formidable challenge that would surely change the course of his destiny, but he tended to surmount it by sacrificing an important part of his life—education over his career.

This decision was heavily influenced by the fact that he’s a late enrollee with an immense school workload to catch up to, even worth mentioning that his chosen program Mass Communication wasn’t aligned with his dream profession to become a professor.

Aside from that, he also shared that his unfortunate financial situation was also the “toughest hindrance” in his school journey.

“Wala ko’y bawn sauna, ambot lang ngano wa ko’y bawn kwarta. Akong klase hantod alas 8 pa sa gabii tas akong money is pang one ride lang sa jeep," he expressed.

Having made a bold decision in the past and considering all influencing factors, Tristan remained committed to hound what he loves doing with no regrets.

Maximizing the Quest for Opportunities

Moving out at such a young age, Tristan somehow found a way to support himself through accepting side jobs.

He made a remarkable name in the eSports industry and accepted notable projects that propelled him to the top.

Tristan worked as a broadcast talent for Mineski and took management roles in companies like RUMBLE ROYALE, AP. Bren, and Cebu’s very own South.gg and even coached Cebuano DOTA teams.

These were the fruits of his labor, an indicator that he was on the right path.

Between 2018 and 2020, he achieved multiple successes, including being the Grand Champion of The Mayor’s Cup 2019, securing the 1st Runner-up position in the Farming Simulator League (FSL) Season 2 qualifiers, and clinching the 2nd Runner-up titles in both the Road to The Nationals Electronic Sports and Gaming Summit (ESGS) and the Acer Predator Cup (APC) 2018.

Tristan viewed this portion of his life as the “sweets of his success.”

Little did they know that there is more to his story than what meets the eye. These attainments were only made possible because of the nights Tristan spent by “sleeping in between jobs.”

Of course, life is not all sweets; it is also about meeting the pressing need to survive a bitter reality. Tristan worked as a barista during the day and a customer representative at night. Life was tough back then for an 18-year-old guy who kept trying to decipher the way out of the labyrinth.

Amidst the pending hardships, he stayed optimistic along the way all in the hope of reaching the finish line. Tristan intensified how much he thrived during those times, yet feeling no amount of exhaustion at all.

“I didn't really feel burnt out or overworked [because] I knew I was working towards something very achievable,” he said.

When one is tested with a tremendous grip of tribulations, their maturity grows, and through these difficulties, they greatly hone their growth as an individual.

Euphoric with achieving more than he expected, he felt that there was still a need for him to go back to his studies.

The Call to U-turn Destination

For anyone who aspires to achieve their aspirations, know that they are valid, even if you encounter setbacks on your path, there’s always a chance to redirect and find purpose moving forward.

Determination is a potent component in this life full of twists and turns, but each challenge that one encounters is an opportunity to learn and grow.

“Whatever I set my mind to, and [if] given a chance to do better this time around, I will,” Fernandez stated.

Being a 24-year-old returnee this academic year brings the “slightest of shame” for him, but this did not deter him from trying again and pursuing his dream of becoming a professor.

“I’m embracing the shamelessness of it. This is me right now. I’m old, and I am getting my life on track,” he added.

In the pursuit of goals, age is never a determining factor.

As long as there is a willingness to strive for better opportunities, growth, and transformation, it remains boundless.

Throughout those experiences, he left a quote that he now instills to motivate him to persevere to finish his education this time.

“On the path towards fulfillment, I am taking the scenic route,” he proudly expressed.

This story is an example that there is no easy way to accomplish goals; there should be obstacles obstructing for us to learn a new lesson, and if ever we make a mistake, at least we come back stronger to break whatever barriers impede us from achieving completion.

“There’s no shame in stepping back; most times it’s how we muster the force to go forward,” Fernandez encouraged.

For anyone who has an ambition and it’s so far away and high up, it’s normal to be tired.

One day you’re gonna look from your feet and you’ll be at your destination.

Tristan Seth Fernandez may be a gamer, but he's now a character in a game of reality, maneuvering the course of his own life.

Jaguars outplay Fighting Maroons in Cesafi Men's Volleyball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars claimed victory against the University of the Philippines-Cebu (UPC) Fighting Maroons, 3-0, in the Cesafi 23 Men's Volleyball tournament at the University of Southern Philippines Foundation (USPF) Gymnasium on Saturday, November 4.

The USJ-R Jaguars withstood the persistent rally of the UPC Fighting Maroons with a series of dynamic hits, securing a 25-18 triumph in the first set.

Jaguars' Ehdrienne Suarez and Ed Vincent Flores delivered strong service aces and powerful attacks for the team, including swift dumps.

Despite a few service errors, the Jaguars increased their offensive campaign in the second set and left their opponent with a 12-point lead, 25-13.

The Jaguars also cemented their win over the Fighting Maroons with defensive blocks, finishing a 25-15 in the final set.

Before the match, Jaguars' Coach Roland Potot made the decision to bench the starting six and instead fielded the second team throughout the game, as some of the starting players failed to meet the pre-match training requirements.

“Akong gitan-aw sa ani nga team is to give them a chance as we need the right attitude sa game and practices. Dili lang skill ang atong gitrabaho as a team, also on their character as well,” Potot said.

Meanwhile, Suarez, an open spiker for the Jaguars, shared the team's commitment in their upcoming games.

“In this season, our goal is to keep it low-key this time kay mag-work hard sa mi sa mga lacking sa among team and make more progress pa jud,” he said.

The Jaguars will next face the Cebu Roosevelt Memorial Colleges (CRMC) Mustangs on November 18 at the same venue.

The Jaguars also cemented their win over the Fighting Maroons with defensive blocks, finishing a 25-15 in the final set.

Before the match, Jaguars' Coach Roland Potot made the decision to bench the starting six and instead fielded the second team throughout the game, as some of the starting players failed to meet the pre-match training requirements.

“Akong gitan-aw sa ani nga team is to give them a chance as we need the right attitude sa game and practices. Dili lang skill ang atong gitrabaho as a team, also on their character as well,” Potot said.

Meanwhile, Suarez, an open spiker for the Jaguars, shared the team's commitment in their upcoming games.

“In this season, our goal is to keep it low-key this time kay mag-work hard sa mi sa mga lacking sa among team and make more progress pa jud,” he said.

The Jaguars will next face the Cebu Roosevelt Memorial Colleges (CRMC) Mustangs on November 18 at the same venue.

#OnTheGo

ADL beats Webmasters and Wildcats, advances to CEL S2 Finals

The Adelante Esports (ADL) Valorant Team won against the University of Cebu Lapu-Lapu and Mandaue (UCLM) Webmasters and the Cebu Institute of Technology-University (CIT-U) in the Cesafi Esports League (CEL) Valorant Season 2 Playoffs on Sunday, October 29, at TNC Cebu.

ADL went head to head with the Webmaster and Wildcats in a best-of-three matches format, securing their spot in the finals

In the first game of their match over the Webmasters, ADL folded to the Webmasters, who gained an early point advantage. ADL kept it close with clutches, keeping the score at its closest at 10-11, but the Webmasters firmly extended their win, 10-13.

The team went neck and neck with the Webmasters in the second game, 5-5, until the former, adapting to the latter’s tactics, pulled ahead with a 2-point lead. The match remained a closely fought contest but ADL kept its margin and triumphed, 13-11.

The third game went down to the wire as ADL and the Webmasters went overtime, trading points. However, ADL found a 2-point advantage to win 17-15.

ADL’s first match against the Wildcats was also closely contested, equalizing into a 12-12 score and going into overtime but their opponents seized a 2-point lead and won 14-10.

They struck back with a vengeance in the next match, gaining a 4-0 lead with Flawless games to boot. The Wildcats rallied to tie 5-5, but ADL recovered and solidified their win at 13-7.

ADL started the third game dominantly with a 5-point lead, 9-4, yet the Wildcats rallied and equalized, bringing the score to 10-9. ADL played hard to close the game as the Wildcats also kept it close with a timely clutch, leading both teams into overtime at 12-12, but ADL finally won the set, 15-13.

The team’s Duelist John Michael “Kel” Canoy, expressed his mixed joy and frustration in the games.

Canoy stated that despite their victory, the team was affected by the absence of one of their members for the season, Kurt Stanley “Astababy” Lando, due to undisclosed reasons.

He further said that they managed to execute their plans and win their games, gunning for the championship title.

“The plan for everything is that we’re going to try our best and we’re gonna be the champion, guys,” he declared.

Meanwhile, ADL Coordinator Hanz Anthony “Troi” Cahilog expressed his pride over the team’s performance and improvement from previous games.

“They tried their best gyod, naningkamot gyod silang tanan bisa’g unsa kalisod. Very proud gyod ko sa ilahang achievement,” he said, sharing his hope for the team to gain their very first CEL Valorant championship as he also acknowledged their future competitors’ strength.

The ADL will face the UC Webmasters for the CEL Season 2 finals at the International Eucharistic Congress (IEC) Convention Center on November 19.

via Jonathan Ricardo | FORWARD Staff Writer
